<table align="center" width="75%">
	<tbody><tr>
		<td align="left" valign="center" width="75%">
			<font face="Helvetica" size="3">
I am an Assistant Professor of <a href="http://politicalscience.tamu.edu/html/home.html">Political Science</a> and Director of the Political Institutions Research Program at <a href="https://www.tamu.edu/">Texas A&M University</a>. I recently received my PhD in <a href="https://polisci.wustl.edu/">political science</a> from <a href="http://wustl.edu/">Washington University in St. Louis</a>, where I was a fellow in the <a href="https://www.nsfgrfp.org/">National Science Foundation Graduate Research Fellowship Program</a> (2011-2014) and a graduate associate for the <a href="http://cerl.wustl.edu/">Center for Empirical Research in the Law (CERL)</a>. My research interests include American politics, political institutions, bureaucracy, courts, policymaking processes, political economy, and formal political theory. My main project studies how institutions such as judicial or executive review affect the incentives for bureaucratic agencies to more effectively craft and implement public policy, and provides insight into how one might design institutions to foster this behavior.
<br>
<br>
For more information on my work, see my <a href="https://www.dropbox.com/s/w4gvj4dspb3o5uz/turnerCV.pdf?dl=0" target="_blank">CV</a>, the papers listed below, or my <a href="http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/cf_dev/AbsByAuth.cfm?per_id=1787251">SSRN page</a>.

	</font>
		</td>
	</tr>
</tbody></table>

